  {
    "topic": "Major Seasonal Festivals in North India",
    "subtopics": [
      {
        "subtopic": "Festivals",
        "content": "• Makar Sankranti (January) – Celebrated across North India with kite flying, bonfires, and feasts. Marks the sun’s transition into Capricorn and the end of winter.\n\n• Baisakhi (April) – Major harvest festival in Punjab and North India, also marks the Sikh New Year and the formation of Khalsa Panth.\n\n• Ladakh Harvest Festival (September) – Celebrated with traditional dances, music, and sports in Ladakh to mark the harvesting season.\n\n• Lohri (January) – Popular in Punjab and Haryana, celebrated with bonfires, folk songs, and distribution of sesame seeds and jaggery sweets.\n\n• Basant Panchami (January/February) – Festival dedicated to Goddess Saraswati, symbolizing the arrival of spring, marked by wearing yellow and kite flying."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "topic": "Major Seasonal Festivals in South India",
    "subtopics": [
      {
        "subtopic": "Festivals",
        "content": "• Onam (August/September) – Kerala’s biggest harvest festival honoring King Mahabali, celebrated with snake boat races, floral carpets (pookalam), and traditional feast (Onam Sadhya).\n\n• Pongal (January) – Tamil Nadu’s harvest festival dedicated to the Sun God, marked by cooking Pongal dish and decorating cattle.\n\n• Ugadi (March/April) – New Year festival in Andhra Pradesh, Telangana, and Karnataka, celebrated with Panchanga reading and preparation of Ugadi Pachadi.\n\n• Vishu (April) – Kerala’s New Year festival, marked by Vishukkani (auspicious sight arrangement) and bursting of crackers."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "topic": "Major Festivals of East & West India",
    "subtopics": [
      {
        "subtopic": "Festivals",
        "content": "• Bhogali Bihu (January) – Assamese harvest festival, celebrated with community feasts, bonfires (Meji), and traditional games.\n\n• Wangala (November) – Harvest festival of the Garo tribe in Meghalaya, dedicated to the Sun God, celebrated with drums (Dama) and traditional dances.\n\n• Ka Pomblang Nongkrem (November) – Important Khasi festival of Meghalaya, where goats are sacrificed to Goddess Ka Blei Synshar for prosperity.\n\n• Nuakhai (August/September) – Agricultural festival of Western Odisha and Chhattisgarh, where newly harvested rice is first offered to deities before consumption.\n\n• Gudi Padwa (March/April) – Maharashtrian New Year, celebrated with Gudi (bamboo stick with silk cloth and garland) hoisted outside homes, symbolizing prosperity.\n\n• Nabanna (November–December) – Bengali harvest festival marking the consumption of new rice, celebrated with community feasts and cultural events."
      }
